body:
I could not reproduce this behavior with a `truffle-config` that has two thunked providers, `ganache1` and `ganache2` that resolve to two running ganache instances (serving port 8545 and 9545 respectively). Note, it is helpful to have both ganache terminals visible while executing the two tests below.

<details><summary>truffle-config.js</summary>

```javascript
const HDWalletProvider = require("@truffle/hdwallet-provider");
const mnemonic = "window twenty cat alone physical foam smoke annual collect pluck educate course";

module.exports = {
  networks: {
    ganache1: {
      provider: () => {
        return new HDWalletProvider( mnemonic, "http://127.0.0.1:8545");
      },
      network_id: "*",
      confirmations: 0,
      timeoutBlocks: 200,
      skipDryRun: true,
    },
    ganache2: {
      provider: () => {
        return new HDWalletProvider( mnemonic, "http://127.0.0.1:9545");
      },
      network_id: "*",
      confirmations: 0,
      timeoutBlocks: 200,
      skipDryRun: true,
    },
  },
  compilers: {
    solc: {
      version: "^0.8.0"
    }
  }
}
```
</details>

- [√] migrate to network ganache1 only resolves the ganache1 provider
   ```console
   $ truffle migrate --network ganache1 --reset
   ```
- [√] migrate to network ganache1 only resolves the ganache2 provider
   
   ```console
   $ truffle migrate --network ganache2 --reset
   ```
